        "text": "# Introduction \nIn J. M. Coetzee’s novel Waiting for the Barbarians the Magistrate of a small town on the outskirts of civilization invites a representative of the Empire into his town and thereby opens the door to hell.  The Magistrate is a good man who sees it as his ethical duty to welcome a stranger to his town and to be helpful to the stranger in accomplishing his mission. In so doing this good man becomes a party to murder, torture, and genocide. This is the ethical dilemma: how can we act ethically in the moment and be purblind to the evil that we unleash at the same time?  Gregory Bateson identifies this dilemma as a double bind: to do good the Magistrate must accommodate evil. \n"
